        "Description": {
            "val": "Environmental Control Equipment:\nThe Family of Environmental Control Equipment (ECE) consists of Environmental Control Units (ECU), Field Refrigeration Systems (FRS), and Cooling and Refrigeration Expeditionary Tool Kits (CREK). These systems provide required heating, cooling, storage, and servicing for systems throughout the Marine Corps. Current efforts seek to replace all legacy ECE with systems of higher reliability and higher efficiency using Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) approved refrigerants, which offer more energy efficiency, enhanced mobility, are easier to repair, and quieter than their predecessors. With environmental control systems consuming 50-70% of tactical electric power in theater, these savings will be a significant contribution to reducing the USMC fuel demand, and lightening the Marine Air-Ground Task Force (MAGTF). The Warfighter benefit includes a decreased logistics footprint, less reliance on petroleum-derived fuels, increased local energy security, and reduced tanker losses (fewer on the road). The operational imperative to reduce fuel usage will consequently reduce refueling operations and exposing Marines to hazardous fuel convoy operations.\nEfforts include the procurement of the following principal end items and ancillary equipment:\n(1) Additional 60,000 BTU\/hr ECUs to sustain Authorized Acquisition Objective (AAO) due to the disposition of ECU variants utilizing R-22 refrigerant, which has been banned by the EPA.\n(2) Small Field Refrigeration Systems (SFRS) replacement. This effort seeks to replace legacy SFRSs to comply with restricting EPA regulations while increasing efficiency, thus reducing overall power requirements\/demands.\n\nInflatable Maritime Structures:\nA fuel bladder designed for autonomous movement under the water's surface that will increase operational persistence and flexibility for distributed operations in contested and uncertain environments, while increasing sustainability, survivability, and maneuverability."
        },
        "Justification": {
            "val": "FY 2019: $0.595M (ACTIVE: $0.595M\/RESERVE: $0.000M)\nFunds purchased 5-Ton 60,000 BTU\/hr ECUs as a result of the disposition of ECU variants utilizing R-22 refrigerant which is banned by the United States Environmental Protection Agency (EPA).\n\nFY 2020: $0.495M (ACTIVE: $0.377M\/RESERVE: $0.118M)\nFunds purchase 60,000 BTU\/hr ECUs due to an increase in the Authorized Acquisition Objective (AAO). The AAO increase is a result of the disposition of ECU variants utilizing R-22 refrigerant which is banned by the United States Environmental Protection Agency (EPA). \n\nFY 2021 Base Appropriation Request: $0.385M (ACTIVE: $0.274M\/RESERVE: $0.111M)\nFunds will continue purchasing 5-Ton 60,000 BTU\/hr ECUs as a result of the disposition of ECU variants utilizing R-22 refrigerant which is banned by the United States Environmental Protection Agency (EPA). Funding decreased from FY20 to FY21 by $0.110M due to this line item has been reprioritized while ensuring the Marine Corps continues to evolve toward a Force that is aligned with the National Defense Strategy.\n\nOCO: \nFY 2019 Overseas Contingency Operations (OCO) Request:  N\/A\nFY 2020 Overseas Contingency Operations (OCO) Request:  N\/A\nFY 2021 Overseas Contingency Operations (OCO) Request:  N\/A"
        },
